'''Okuma Kabuto Festival''' (お熊甲祭) is the annual [[Reisai|regular festival]] of {{ill|Kumakabuto Arakashi Hiko Shrine|ja|久麻加夫都阿良加志比古神社|12=draft}}, located in {{ill|Nanao|ja|七尾市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|12=draft}}, in the {{ill|Nakajima, Ishikawa|lt=Nakajima|ja|中島町 (石川県)|12=draft}} district of Miyamae. Held every year on {{ill|September 20|ja|9月20日|12=draft}}, it is also referred to as the '''Hatsuka Festival''' (二十日祭, Hatsuka Matsuri or Hatsuka Sai).<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Okuma Kabuto Festival: A Nationally Designated Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|url=https://www.city.nanao.lg.jp/koryu-s/event/9gatsu/okumakabuto-.html|website=Nanao City|access-date=2022-10-15|language=ja}}</ref> It is one of the {{ill|Four Major Festivals of Nanao|ja|七尾四大祭|12=draft}} along with the {{ill|Seihakusai|ja|青柏祭|12=draft}}, {{ill|Mukōda Fire Festival|ja|向田の火祭り|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Ishizaki Hōtō Festival|ja|石崎奉燈祭|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.nanao.lg.jp/kikaku-s/shise/sesaku/1sogokekaku/honpen/documents/kihonkeikaku_1_4_5.pdf|title=Basic Plan: Chapter 1, Arts and Culture|access-date=2024-08-04|publisher=Nanao City|page=88}}</ref>{{Refnest|group="Note"|text=The Seihakusai, Ishizaki Hōtō Festival, {{ill|Nanao Gion Festival|ja|七尾祇園祭|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Nanao Port Festival|ja|七尾港まつり|12=draft}} are sometimes listed as the four major festivals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yamaguchi-ev.com/ishikawa-event/1692/|title=Events in Ishikawa Prefecture in May|access-date=2024-08-04|publisher=Yamaguchi Corporation}}</ref>}}
Due to its unique use of massive framed banners (''waku-hata'') measuring up to 20 meters, the festival is designated as the '''Framed Banner Procession of the Kumakabuto Hatsuka Festival''' (熊甲二十日祭の枠旗行事), a [[Nationally Designated Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property]] since 1981.<ref name="database">{{国指定文化財等データベース2|name=Framed Banner Procession of the Kumakabuto Hatsuka Festival|register=302|item=61|year=1981|jyear=昭和56|month=1|date=21|cat1=Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property}}</ref><ref name=":0" />
== Overview ==
Kumakabuto Arakashi Hiko Shrine is the main shrine of 19 subordinate shrines located throughout the {{ill|Nakajima Town|ja|中島町 (石川県)|12=draft}} villages of {{ill|Kumaki|ja|熊木村|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nakajima|ja|中島町中島|12=draft}}, {{ill|Saigishi|ja|西岸村|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Toyokawa|ja|豊川村|12=draft}}.<ref name=":0" /> During the '''Okuma Kabuto Festival''', portable shrines (''mikoshi'') from all 19 subordinate shrines, each accompanied by vibrant red woolen-framed banners up to 20 meters tall, gather at the main shrine.<ref name=":0" /> The day begins with a procession led by {{ill|Sarutahiko|ja|猿田彦|12=draft}}, with all the subordinate shrines arriving at the main shrine by noon.<ref name=":0" /> Following a ceremony, Sarutahiko performs a spirited dance in the shrine grounds to the sound of gongs and drums.<ref name=":0" />
In the afternoon, the main shrine’s ''mikoshi'' leads the procession to the {{ill|Otabisho|ja|御旅所|12=draft}} at Kamohara. Here, a dramatic banner maneuver called ''Shimada Kuzushi,'' which involves lowering the framed banners to ground level, is performed.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Dictionary of Festivals|editor={{ill|Kazuhiko Sato|ja|佐藤和彦|12=draft}}|publisher={{ill|Tokyodo Publishing|ja|東京堂出版|12=draft}}|page=321}}</ref> Each shrine competes in displays of skill before the festival concludes with a purification ritual.<ref name=":0" />
== Genzo Pilgrimage ==
In {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|12=draft}}, newlywed women traditionally participate in a ritual called ''Genzo Mairi,'' where they visit the {{ill|Ujigami|ja|氏神|12=draft}} shrine to gain community acceptance.<ref>{{cite book|editor= 山と渓谷社|title= カラー 日本のまつり|publisher= [[山と渓谷社]]|year= 1967|page=158}}</ref> During the '''Okuma Kabuto Festival''', newlywed women from outside the parish community secretly perform their first shrine visit alongside their mothers. The women dress in formal attire, carrying tiered lunch boxes filled with food to be shared with the shrine attendees. Upon returning home, these lunch boxes are filled with pre-ordered sweets, which are distributed to relatives and neighbors.<ref>{{cite book|editor= 山と渓谷社|title= カラー 日本のまつり|publisher= [[山と渓谷社]]|year= 1967|page=158}}</ref>
