Kumakabuto Arakashi Hiko Shrine is the main shrine of 19 subordinate shrines located throughout the {{ill|Nakajima Town|ja|中島町 (石川県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakajima Town|qq=}} villages of {{ill|Kumaki|ja|熊木村|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumaki|qq=}}, {{ill|Nakajima|ja|中島町中島|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakajima|qq=}}, {{ill|Saigishi|ja|西岸村|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saigishi|qq=}}, and {{ill|Toyokawa|ja|豊川村|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyokawa|qq=}}.<ref name=":0" /> During the '''Okuma Kabuto Festival''', portable shrines (''mikoshi'') from all 19 subordinate shrines, each accompanied by vibrant red woolen-framed banners up to 20 meters tall, gather at the main shrine.<ref name=":0" /> The day begins with a procession led by {{ill|Sarutahiko|ja|猿田彦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sarutahiko|qq=}}, with all the subordinate shrines arriving at the main shrine by noon.<ref name=":0" /> Following a ceremony, Sarutahiko performs a spirited dance in the shrine grounds to the sound of gongs and drums.<ref name=":0" /> 

In the afternoon, the main shrine’s ''mikoshi'' leads the procession to the {{ill|Otabisho|ja|御旅所|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otabisho|qq=}} at Kamohara. Here, a dramatic banner maneuver called ''Shimada Kuzushi,'' which involves lowering the framed banners to ground level, is performed.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Dictionary of Festivals|editor={{ill|Kazuhiko Sato|ja|佐藤和彦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kazuhiko Sato|qq=}}|publisher={{ill|Tokyodo Publishing|ja|東京堂出版|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokyodo Publishing|qq=}}|page=321}}</ref> Each shrine competes in displays of skill before the festival concludes with a purification ritual.<ref name=":0" />

== Genzo Pilgrimage == 

In {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noto Province|qq=}}, newlywed women traditionally participate in a ritual called ''Genzo Mairi,'' where they visit the {{ill|Ujigami|ja|氏神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ujigami|qq=}} shrine to gain community acceptance.<ref>{{cite book|editor= 山と渓谷社|title= カラー 日本のまつり|publisher= [[山と渓谷社]]|year= 1967|page=158}}</ref> During the '''Okuma Kabuto Festival''', newlywed women from outside the parish community secretly perform their first shrine visit alongside their mothers. The women dress in formal attire, carrying tiered lunch boxes filled with food to be shared with the shrine attendees. Upon returning home, these lunch boxes are filled with pre-ordered sweets, which are distributed to relatives and neighbors.<ref>{{cite book|editor= 山と渓谷社|title= カラー 日本のまつり|publisher= [[山と渓谷社]]|year= 1967|page=158}}</ref>

